R markdown = R code + Markdown

Markdown

  • Markdown is a text-to-HTML conversion tool

  • Markdown allows you to write using an easy to read/write plain text format, then convert it to structurally valid HTML (or PDF, Word) file.

    • The Markdown text format allows to insert bullet points, numbered lists, text in bold/italics, URL links etc.

  • To create Markdown file, in RStudio: clikc File > New file... > R script/Text file and save that file with extension .md

  • To compile Markdown file into HTML file (default) or other (PDF, Word): click Preview tab in RStudio

  • Example:

R Markdown

  • R Markdown is a file format that allows to mix text written in Markdown with R code chunks

  • R code chunks contain actual R code which gets executed when we compile the R Markdown file

    • The output of the R code execution (numbers, tables, plots) is displayed in the output document by default

    • The R code itself is also displayed in the output document by default (can be hidden)

  • To create R Markdown file in RStudio, we need to have rmarkdown R package installed:

    install.packages("rmarkdown")

    Then click File > New File > R Markdown...;

  • To compile R Markdown file into HTML file (default) or other (PDF, Word) into HTML document: click Knit tab in RStudio (again, note knit output options)

  • To change output file to PDF:

HW1 - Problem 12

    1. A valid density \(f(x)\) should satisfy two conditions: 1). \(f(x)\geq 0\) for all \(x\). 2). \(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)dx=1\). [Reference: Lecture 2, slide 26/43 - PDF]

    • \(f(x)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x)\geq 0\) for \(x>0\).

    • \(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)dx=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\int_0^{\infty}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x)=\frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\Gamma(\alpha)=1\).

    1. \(S(t)=1-F(t)\). Integrate the density from 0 to \(t\) to compute \(F(t)\): \(F(t) = \int_{-\infty}^tf(x)dx.\)

    1. This function is greater than 0. To show that it integrates to 1, we use the change of variable formula \(y=x/\beta\):
    • \(\int_0^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{\alpha}\Gamma(\alpha)}x^{\alpha-1}\exp(-x/\beta)=\frac{1}{\beta^{\alpha}\Gamma(\alpha)}\int_0^{\infty}(\beta y)^{\alpha-1}\exp(-y)\beta dy=1\).

    1. The dgamma() function returns the density of gamma distribution.
x = seq(0,15,0.1)
plot(x,dgamma(x,shape=1,scale=1), main = "Gamma densities", xlab = "x", ylab = "Density", type = "l")
lines(x,dgamma(x,shape=2,scale=1), col=2)
lines(x,dgamma(x,shape=3,scale=1), col=3)
lines(x,dgamma(x,shape=2,scale=2), col=4)
lines(x,dgamma(x,shape=2,scale=0.5), col=5)

HW1 - Problem 13

    1. The function is nonnegative by definition. Use change of variable formula \(y=x^{\gamma}\), we have \(dy=\gamma x^{\gamma-1}\). Therefore
      \(\int_0^{\infty} \frac{\gamma}{\beta}x^{\gamma-1}\exp(-x^{\gamma}/\beta)dx=\int_0^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta}exp(-y/\beta)dy=-\exp(-y/\beta)\big|_0^{\infty}=1\).

    1. Solve the equation \(F(t)=0.5\). Note since \(S(t) = 1 - F(t)\), this equals sovling \(S(t)=0.5\), and we already have \(S(t)\) from b.

    1. The rweibull() function returns the Weibull density.
x = seq(0,5,0.02)
plot(x,dweibull(x,shape=0.5,scale=1), main = "Weibull densities", xlab = "x", ylab = "Density", type = "l",ylim=c(0,2))
lines(x,dweibull(x,shape=1,scale=1), col=2)
lines(x,dweibull(x,shape=1.5,scale=1), col=3)
lines(x,dweibull(x,shape=5,scale=2), col=4)
lines(x,dweibull(x,shape=2,scale=0.5), col=5)

The same plot can be made using curve() function.

x = seq(0,5,0.02)
curve(dweibull(x,shape=0.5,scale=1), from=0, to=5, main = "Weibull densities", xlab = "x", ylab = "Density", type = "l",ylim=c(0,2))
curve(dweibull(x,shape=1,scale=1), col=2, add=TRUE)
curve(dweibull(x,shape=1.5,scale=1), col=3, add=TRUE)
curve(dweibull(x,shape=5,scale=2), col=4, add=TRUE)
curve(dweibull(x,shape=2,scale=0.5), col=5, add=TRUE)

HW1 - Problem 6

    1. Let \(X=F^{-1}(U)\). Since \(F(\cdot)\) is strictly increasing, it is invertible and \(F^{-1}(\cdot)\) is also strictly increasing. The CDF of \(X\) is \[F_X(x)=Pr(X\leq x)=Pr(F^{-1}(U)\leq x).\] Since \(F(\cdot)\) and \(F^{-1}(\cdot)\) are both strictly increasing, the event \(\{F^{-1}(U)\leq x\}\) is equivalent to the event \(\{U\leq F(x)\}\). Therefore \[Pr(F^{-1}(U)\leq x)=Pr(U \leq F(x)).\] Integrating the density of \(U\) we have \[Pr(U \leq F(x))=\int_{0}^{F(x)} 1du=F(x).\] Hence \(F^{-1}(U)\) has distribution function \(F(\cdot)\).

    1. First simulate an iid sample \(\{U_i\}_{i=1,2,...n}\) from Uniform[0,1] using function runif(). Then apply transformation \(X_i=F^{-1}(U_i)\). \(X_i\) have cdf \(F(\cdot)\).

    1. Simulate uniform random variables and apply the normal quantile function to obtain normal variables.
    • Note: qqnorm() function produces a normal Q-Q plot. That is, it compares sample quantiles from provided vector of values aganist theoretical \(N(0,1)\) quantiles values. qqline() function adds a line \(y=x\). If the provided vector of values comes from distribution similar to \(N(0,1)\), then the points in the QQ plot will approximately lie on the line \(y=x\).
# Simulate 1000 variables to better view the distribution.
set.seed(123)
U = runif(1000, min=0, max=1)
X = qnorm(U)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
hist(U, main="Uniform")
hist(X, main="Normal")

# Compare distribution of generated X vector aganist normal distribution
qqnorm(X)
qqline(X, col=2, lty=2)

To simulate from other distributions, generate uniform R.Vs and apply corresponding quantile functions (qexp() for exponential, qgamma() for gamma distribution,).
